text: I appreciate that. It is a very simple idea. It is to try to bring the street together for a day of really differentiated content. I love, you know, that's why I love doing the podcast. I love engaging with clients. So this idea of trying to crowdsource ideas and intelligence, I think financial markets absolutely require us to lean on others in the industry, even our competitors to get smarter, right? I mean, who the heck knows a lot about the debt ceiling? You're going to require others to learn more about that or, you know, about the XIV event or, you know, things like this inflation. So we're all learning from each other. And so I love hosting events and MacroMinds is effectively a charitable endeavor where we host this event each year, we're raising money for children's education, student education, which I can't speak enough about. I'm not going to talk about how critical that is. You have a young child. I've got three, two in high school, one in college. You know, education is everything, right? That's what we want for our kids. And it's a luxury that many parents are just not afforded. The pandemic made it so much worse. So to have a chance to bring the buy side and the sell side and the allocator community together, raise money. We do it for three different charities per year that are engaged in student education in the New York tri-state area. And we just try to host a great event with panel discussions. So we did our third this year. I always have to take a little bit of time off afterwards, but you know, I'll start to gear it up and hopefully by June of next year, we, you know, pull off another great event with some quality speakers. Corey, you have an invite. I hope you can make it again. And yeah, thanks for asking about it. It's been a real joy to be able to bring this together. We've raised $1.3 million so far across our three events so far. Thank you.
